I too used to support the Modi government from 2014 to 2024. I supported the Modi government in every aspect. When they introduced GST, I said okay, no problem, sales tax will be replaced by GST tax, which we will have to pay anyway. In 2018, they introduced tax on dividends and capital gains tax, but I thought that since we earn, we can pay tax. However, now Nirmala ji has taken taxes to a whole new level, increasing capital gains tax and retaining tax on dividends. As investors and traders, we are paying around 42% tax, and after that, we still have to pay GST, road tax, toll tax, and almost all taxes. Now it feels like we are working for the government. I'm not saying there should be no tax, but there should be some limit to it. Now it seems that supporting the Modi government further won't be right.

DARK TRIAD TRAIT
in 2010, Dr Peter Jonason, then assistant professor of psychology at the University of Western Florida, and his co-author, Gregory Webster, assistant professor of psychology at the University of Florida, developed the "Dirty Dozen" rating scale, or a 12-item methodology, to measure Dark Triad traits. [1]

Jonason and Webster's measure asks people to rate themselves against these questions:

I tend to manipulate others to get my way.
I have used deceit or lied to get my way.
I have used flattery to get my way.
I tend to exploit others towards my own end.
I tend to lack remorse.
I tend to not be too concerned with morality or the morality of my actions.
I tend to be callous or insensitive.
I tend to be cynical.
I tend to want others to admire me.
I tend to want others to pay attention to me.
I tend to seek prestige or status.
I tend to expect special favors from others.

Here's a detailed recipe for Chicken Biryani:

Ingredients

For the Chicken Marinade:

500g chicken, cut into pieces

1 cup yogurt

1 tablespoon ginger-garlic paste

1 teaspoon turmeric powder

1 teaspoon red chili powder

1 teaspoon garam masala powder

Salt to taste

For the Rice:

2 cups basmati rice

4 cups water

4 green cardamom pods

4 cloves

2 bay leaves

1 cinnamon stick

Salt to taste

For the Biryani:

3 tablespoons ghee or oil

2 large onions, thinly sliced

2 tomatoes, chopped

2 green chilies, slit

1 tablespoon ginger-garlic paste

1/2 teaspoon turmeric powder

1 teaspoon red chili powder

1 teaspoon garam masala powder

1 teaspoon cumin seeds

1/2 cup chopped cilantro (coriander leaves)

1/2 cup chopped mint leaves

A pinch of saffron soaked in 1/4 cup warm milk

Fried onions (for garnish)

Fresh cilantro and mint leaves (for garnish)

Instructions

Preparing the Chicken:

In a large bowl, combine yogurt, ginger-garlic paste, turmeric powder, red chili powder, garam masala powder, and salt. Mix well.

Add the chicken pieces to the marinade and coat them evenly. Let it marinate for at least 1 hour, or overnight in the refrigerator for better flavor.

Preparing the Rice:

Rinse the basmati rice under cold water until the water runs clear.

In a large pot, bring 4 cups of water to a boil. Add the green cardamom pods, cloves, bay leaves, cinnamon stick, and salt.

Add the rice to the boiling water and cook until it is 70% cooked (it should still have a bite to it). Drain the rice and set aside.

Preparing the Biryani:

In a large, heavy-bottomed pan, heat the ghee or oil over medium heat.

Add the sliced onions and saut├й until they turn golden brown and caramelized. Remove half of the onions and set them aside for garnish.

Add the cumin seeds to the remaining onions in the pan and saut├й for a minute.

Add the ginger-garlic paste and green chilies. Saut├й until the raw smell disappears.

Add the chopped tomatoes, turmeric powder, red chili powder, and garam masala powder. Cook until the tomatoes turn mushy and the oil starts to separate.

Add the marinated chicken to the pan and cook until the chicken is half-cooked and the spices are well blended.

Add the chopped cilantro and mint leaves. Mix well.

Layering the Biryani:

Preheat your oven to 180┬░C (350┬░F).

In a large ovenproof dish, start layering the biryani. Begin with a layer of the partially cooked chicken mixture, followed by a layer of the partially cooked rice.

Repeat the layers, finishing with a layer of rice on top.

Drizzle the saffron-soaked milk over the top layer of rice.

Cover the dish with aluminum foil or a tight-fitting lid.

Bake in the preheated oven for 30-40 minutes, or until the chicken is fully cooked and the flavors have melded together.

Garnishing and Serving:

Once the biryani is done, let it rest for 10 minutes before opening.

Garnish with fried onions, fresh cilantro, and mint leaves.

Serve hot with raita, pickle, and a side salad.

Enjoy your delicious Chicken Biryani!

I'm posting this with the hope that you'll shed light on an urgent issue. The 126-year-old Mullaperiyar Dam is no longer safeтАФhydrologically, seismically, and structurallyтАФto hold water at the current level of 152 feet. This poses a severe threat to the lives of over 5 million people in Kerala. We understand that five districts in Tamil Nadu rely on this dam for water, and we're not opposed to sharing this vital resource with our brothers and sisters there. However, our safety is equally important.

There is a viable solution to this problem, as suggested by the 2014 Supreme Court verdict. The court proposed the possibility of constructing another tunnel at the 50-foot level, which would allow the water level in the dam to be lowered. This way, Tamil Nadu would continue to receive sufficient water, while Kerala could be safeguarded from the catastrophic risk of the dam failing.

Unfortunately, despite this solution, no decision has been made, and both the Kerala and Tamil Nadu governments seem to be at a standstill. We plead for your voice in this matter. To the international community, we, the students of Bangladesh, seek your support and solidarity in our ongoing struggle against the reinstatement of the quota system in government jobs. The recent decision to bring back this system has sparked widespread protests and unrest across our universities, as we believe it undermines meritocracy and perpetuates discrimination.
**Our Situation:**
1. **Historical Context:** The quota system was initially introduced to address historical injustices and ensure representation for marginalized groups, including descendants of freedom fighters, women, ethnic minorities, and individuals from underdeveloped regions. However, this system reserved 56% of government jobs, leaving a limited number of positions for general candidates based on meritуАР11тАаsourceуАС.
2. **2018 Reforms:** In 2018, following extensive student protests, the government abolished the quotas for first and second-class government jobs, implementing a more merit-based recruitment process. This was seen as a significant step towards fairness and equality in public service recruitmentуАР10тАаsourceуАС.
3. **Recent Developments:** In 2024, the High Court ruled the 2018 abolition illegal, reinstating the quota system. The Supreme Court upheld this decision, sparking renewed protests. Students are demanding the reimplementation of the 2018 policy and the cancellation of the reinstated quotasуАР10тАаsourceуАСуАР11тАаsourceуАС.
4. **Current Protests:** Our protests involve thousands of students from various institutions, who have taken to the streets, blocked major intersections, and disrupted traffic to voice our demands. We believe that the quota system, as it stands, is unfair and discriminates against deserving candidates who do not benefit from these quotasуАР9тАаsourceуАСуАР11тАаsourceуАС.
**Our Appeal:**
We appeal to the international community, human rights organizations, and governments to support our cause and advocate for a fair and just recruitment process in Bangladesh. Your solidarity can amplify our voices and help bring about meaningful change.
**What You Can Do:**
1. **Raise Awareness:** Share our story and the challenges we face on social media, in the press, and through your networks.
2. **Advocate:** Urge your governments and international organizations to call for a fair resolution that respects merit-based recruitment while addressing historical injustices in a balanced manner.
3. **Support:** Provide moral and, if possible, material support to our movement, ensuring our safety and the continuation of our struggle for justice.
Together, we can push for a system that upholds fairness, equality, and meritocracy, ensuring a brighter future for all students and job seekers in Bangladesh.

The Current Global Economic System
The current global economic system is outdated and primarily based on business models, with GDP contributions centered around Purchasing Power Parity (PPP). This employer-employee model essentially resembles a slave system. People develop skills and chase purchasing power, perpetuating this cycle.

In India today, educational institutions and colleges are ubiquitous, meaning all necessary human skills are readily available. There is no need for anyone to leave their place or chase purchasing power for education, work, or healthcare. Pursuing purchasing power is the root cause of problems such as unemployment, poverty, hunger, anger, hatred, betrayal, crime, corruption, and terrorism. Purchasing power also reduces humans to a primal state, filling them with desire, greed, anger, and arrogance. Business models are based on Purchasing Power Parity. People, whether rich or poor, become slaves to money, engaging in activities such as working for wages, salaries, compensation, and remuneration (royalties, brokerage, commissions, dividends, bonuses, etc.), as well as seeking profit, revenue, and income. They also become slaves to the tax system, which controls economic conditions through business models that foster competition and discrimination.

The economic system must shift to an economic model based on GDP per capita. This model Is driven by the EarthтАЩs resources, operating on the principles of need and value systems, ethics, governance, and mutual interdependence, supported by R&D and service to others. The key pillars of this economic model include production, consumption, involvement, and management. In India, there is potential for unlimited cooperative development of unlimited commodities through Public Sector Undertakings (PSUs), creating a single industry trade channel for all.

Development should happen per capita in every region. Development is analogous to the optimal functioning of any running thing like a car. Just as a car needs all its parts to function correctly for efficient operation, societies thrive when all human capabilities are recognized, developed, and utilized to their fullest potential. Each skill contributes uniquely, much like each component contributes to the functionality of a car. When human skills are integrated harmoniously, they create a powerful engine for societal progress, driving innovation, productivity, and sustainable growth. Therefore, true development arises not merely from individual skills alone but from their collective and synergistic integration.
Note:The existing business model based on outdated Purchase Power Parity, Proprietor Act, Partnership Act, and Companies Act is no longer viable. It must be reformed to be based on Per Capita income to ensure sustainable economic empowerment.

The global economic paradigm operates in reverse, predominantly driven by business/ models. At its core, the GDP (PPP) тАУ Purchasing Power Parity тАУ serves as the engine of the entire global economy. This economic framework is deeply entrenched in a structure resembling modern-day servitude, notably characterized by an employer-employee dynamic and an intricate tax system.

The worldтАЩs economic system is functioning in reverse from micro to macro level; it revolves around business models. GDP (PPP) тАУ Purchasing Power Parity тАУ drives the entire global economy. The worldтАЩs economy is built on a system akin to slavery, particularly an employer- employee model and a tax system. People often become enslaved to the pursuit of wealth, whether through working for wages, salary compensation, remuneration (such as royalty, brokerage, commission, dividend, bonus), profit, revenue, or income. Moreover, the tax system further binds individuals to economic conditions, controlled by business models that foster  competition and discrimination. Furthermore, the educational, healthcare, and employment infrastructures worldwide are intricately tied to the concept of Purchasing Power Parity.

Consequently, competition within this system breeds discrimination, exacerbating issues such as unemployment, poverty, hunger, anger, crime, and corruption. These societal maladies are fundamentally rooted in the pursuit of purchasing power parity, perpetuating a cycle of spystemic challenges. The education, healthcare, and employment systems worldwide are all based on Purchasing Power Parity. Competition fosters discrimination, Pursuing purchasing power parity is leading us to create our own problems. For example, the banking sectorтАЩs model is grounded in the business model, driven by purchasing power, which shifts people from their needs to desires.

Purchasing power is the root cause of diverse lifestyles and the instigator of troubles among individuals. Business models within this construct operate on metrics such as Real GDP, Purchasing Power Parity, and Nominal GDP per Capita. However, the economic model advocates for a shift towards Per Capita Real GDP as the primary metric. This shift is crucial for economic reform, as it aims to address human suffering by prioritizing individual well-being over material wealth. By embracing this model, we can foster a more equitable distribution of resources and opportunities across society, thus mitigating the adverse effects of purchasing power-centric economics. In essence, the transition towards a Per Capita-based economic model holds the key to fostering sustainable and inclusive growth on a global scale.

Business models operate on Real GDP Purchasing Power Parity, and Nominal GDP per Capita. However, the economic model focuses on Per Capita Real GDP. Per Capita Real GDP influences Nominal GDP and Purchasing Power. To implement economic reform, we must alleviate human suffering by replacing purchasing power with Per Capita and replacing the business model with the economic model. The education, healthcare, and employment systems should be Per Capita- based rather than purchasing power-based. This shift would ensure a fairer distribution of resources and opportunities, prioritizing individual needs and capabilities over their purchasing power.

The economic system should run solely on an economic model where the Earth provides both life and work, something unique to our world. GDP (Per Capita) should operate based on need, which is a common aspect of life and is interconnected. It should function on value development, ethics, and governance. It should run on R&D and the economic model itself.

Advocating for a shift towards a Per Capita Real GDP as the primary economic metric is crucial for reform. This approach prioritizes individual well-being over purely economic indicators, aiming to alleviate human suffering and promote equitable distribution of resources and opportunities.

Embracing a Per Capita-based economic model allows societies to mitigate the negative impacts associated with a focus on purchasing power-centric economics. In essence, transitioning towards a Per Capita-based economic approach addresses immediate societal challenges while laying the groundwork for long-term sustainable growth. By focusing on investing in human capital, innovation, and sustainable practices, societies can build resilience and ensure equitable development for all.

Mind and Intellect
Humans possess both the mind and the intellect. The mind gives rise to worries, while the intellect leads to progress. The mind harbors desires, which in todayтАЩs modern world is referred to as business, and the entire process of achieving these desires or dreams is called a business model. The intellect focuses on necessities and connects us to the earth, our loved ones, and each other, functioning through ethics and governance. When each person works on the land per capita, the result is progress and increased purchasing power for everyone.

The entire world economic systemтАФincluding education, work, and judicial systemsтАФis based on business models and purchasing power parity. To gain purchasing power, people develop their skills and operate within the business model, contributing to GDP in the form of wages, salaries, compensation, profit, and revenue, and paying taxes to the government for essential services like food, medicine, and education. In an economic model, GDP contribution per capita, meaning working on the land, results in increased purchasing power and progress for all.

An economic model focuses on production, consumption, Involvement, and management with the help of research and development. In an economic model, competition exists to build each otherтАЩs strengths. In a cooperative model, commodity production happens within a single industry. However, the desire for purchasing power and living life according to it, or chasing it throughout life, leads to negative outcomes like unemployment, poverty, hunger, anger, hatred, betrayal, violence, corruption, crime, and terrorism.

The business model fundamentally relies on purchasing power, leading to Inflation in commodities and currency values because purchasing power is produced. There is competition and discrimination based on name, identity, caste, and race. Due to similar desires among different people, competition and discrimination arise, leading to the wastage of both the finished product and purchasing power.

## ЁЯП╣ ST Community: Unfairly Dragged into the Supreme Court's Verdict? ЁЯдФ

The Supreme Court's recent verdict has paved the way for sub-classification within the SC community. However, the inclusion of the ST community in this judgment raises several concerns. 

The sub-classification of the ST community was  **never a point of discussion**. There was no law, no debate; yet, the Supreme Court  **unilaterally**  chose to  **drag**  the ST community into this verdict. 

This is  **unfair**  because:

* **Distinct Identity:** SC and ST communities have  **different historical backgrounds**  and  **social realities**.
* **Constitutional Provision:** The Constitution already has a separate provision for the  **ST community of Assam**, indicating that the framers of the Constitution had  **already implemented sub-classification within the ST community**.
* **No Demand:** There has been  **no demand**  from the ST community for sub-classification.

This verdict poses a  **threat**  to the  **distinct identity**  and  **rights**  of the ST community. The Supreme Court needs to  **reconsider**  this aspect and ensure  **justice**  for the ST community.

Federal Income Tax Brackets Overview

The U.S. currently has seven federal income tax brackets, with rates of 10%, 12%, 22%, 24%, 32%, 35% and 37%. If youтАЩre one of the lucky few to earn enough to fall into the 37% bracket, that doesnтАЩt mean that the entirety of your taxable income will be subject to a 37% tax. Instead, 37% is your top marginal tax rate.

With a┬аmarginal tax rate, you pay that rate only on the amount of your income that falls into a certain range.┬аTo understand how marginal rates work, consider the bottom tax rate of 10%. For single filers in 2024, all income between $0 and $11,600 is subject to a 10% tax rate. If you have $11,800 in taxable income in 2024, the first┬а$11,600 is subject to the 10% rate and the remaining $200 is subject to the tax rate of the next bracket (12%).

Rs.2 crore тАУ Rs.5 crore: 25% (Old tax regime), 25% (New tax regime)
Rs.5 crore тАУ Rs.10 crore: 37% (Old tax regime), 25% (New tax regime)
More than Rs.10 crore: 37% (Old tax regime), 25% (New tax regime)

Dhruv,   I think you are reaching the wrong conclusion on the impact of long term capital gains tax on speculation in non-financial assets.  If you run more real-world examples, you will realize that people who bought their assets in recent years stand to gain more from lower long-term capital gains tax reduction relative to what they would lose because indexation benefits are gone.  Speculators belong to this category of people since they seek to make quick gains and sell after holding the asset for 1 year.  The new tax policy actually benefits such people.  So, this could spur more speculation.  I could be wrong, but this is worth some more thought.
